    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nFor some people it is quite a common task to add empty space between functions / statements in code. Usually, this is done by using `ok` or `Oj` and then moving to the previous line. But this isn't ideal because:\n- it doesn't maintain exact cursor position. if we use a mark, the command becomes a lot longer\n- we can't create multiple lines this way by prefixing it with a count \n\n### Expected behavior\n\nI propose that there will be added 2 default keymappings to add add empty line above and below:\n\n```lua\nvim.keymap.set(\"n\", \"gL\", \"<cmd>call append(line('.') - 1, repeat([''], v:count1))<CR>\", { desc = \"empty line above\" })\n\nvim.keymap.set(\"n\", \"gl\", \"<cmd>call append(line('.'), repeat([''], v:count1))<CR>\", { desc = \"add empty line below\" })\n```\n\nthe keymappings are just a suggestion from me , since `go` and `gO` are both taken and `gl` & `gL` are both available\n\nmnemonic: \"L\" for \"**L**ine\"",
